Third places - Preliminary analysis

Alexandre Naud

July 14th, 2021

These analysis follow the work of Firth CL and al., (2020) presented at the American Public Health Association Annual Meeting and Expo (October 2020).

See this presentation

A. InterAct - Montreal

  • Cross-sectionnal observationnal studies
  • 1155 participant aged from 18 to 85 years old and living in the Montreal area
  • 833 have completed the VERITAS social questionnaire

B. Data preparation

Cleaning other locations

  • In this study, participant could identify locations as others
  • They represent 641 of the 18184 reported locations (3.5%)
  • Most of these locations could be reclassified accordings to the verbatime description
  • I created 5 new categories: Community organization, Daycare, Library, Shopping center and Store
  • 563 (88%) were reclassified, 364 (65%) were in new categories

What we define as third places

  • Categories defined by Firth CL and al.:
    • Park
    • Restaurant, bar and caf
    • sports
    • Cultural and non-physical leisure activity
    • Religious or spiritual
    • Volunteering
  • I added the following:
    • Community organization
    • Shopping center

Calculating the number of people seen third places

Transforming group data

  • How many people are in groups?
  • If we use group size, we bias the number of people towards large value
    • E.g. Some groups have size > 100
  • Weight by the square root of group size

Transforming group in \(\sqrt{n}\) where \(n = group_size\)

Counting people by third places

  • A participant can have several third places
  • Similar people can be comonly seen accross third places

Counting people seen in restaurant. In this hypothetical example, the participant see 10 people across two restaurants

Description of the variables used in the following analysis

Socio-demographic

Code Description Type Raw or Generated
age Number of years lived continuous raw
age_group Which age categories categorial generated
gender Current gender identity categorial raw
group_white White or non-white categorial generated
income Annual household income categorial raw

Well-being

Description Code Type Raw or Generated
pwb Personnal well-being index continuous raw

Visited third places

Description Code Type Raw or Generated
park Number of visited parks ordinal generated
sport visited sport facility ordinal generated
cultural cultural and leisure ordinal generated
volunteering volontering activities ordinal generated
religious religious and spiritual ordinal generated
restaurant restaurant, bar and caf ordinal generated
third all third places ordinal generated

People seen in third places

Description Code Type Raw or Generated
people_important Number of important people seen in third places ordinal generated
people_socialize people with whom one like to socialize ordinal generated
people_individuals individualy reported people ordinal generated
people_all people (including those from groups) ordinal generated

These variables were also stratified by third places type (e.g.number of important people seen in park)

ACME: Average Causal Mediation Effect

ADE: Average Direct Effect

Both statistics represents the population averages of these causal mediation and direct effects

Total effect: ACME + ADE

Prop. Mediated: The proportion of the effect of the IV on the DV that goes through the mediator

Reference: Imai K, Keele L, Tingley D, Yamamoto T (2011). Unpacking the Black Box: Learning about Causal Mechanisms from Experimental and Observational Studies.American Political Science Review,105(4), 765789. URL

G. Take Home

Bivariate

  • Number of third places seem to increase with income
  • Number of cultural/leisure and volunteering seems to increase with age
  • Number of parks seems higher among 25-44 years old
  • People seen in third places seems higher among 25-44 years old and among women
  • People seen in third places seems to increase with income
  • Restaurant, park and cultural/leisure, and sport seems to be the locations were participants see more people
  • Volunteering seems also important activities to see people at 65+ years and more

Regression

  • Direct effect of number of third places on well-being is significative
  • Mediation by number of people seen is non significative

H. Next step

Problem with count - Duplicated locations

  • Different activities happening in a same location
  • Using similar geographic coordinates: 1344 activites in 626 locations
  • Similar location have also close coordinates

Problem with networks without edges

  • 85 socio-spatial have no edges (nobody are seen in any locations)
  • Missing information?

What do we do with missing income information?

  • 65 participants have not reported income
  • Imputation?

Use a more appropriate regression models in the mediation analysis?

  • Quadratic term for ceiling effect?
  • Model adapted for count data with multiple zero (people_all)
    • e.g.Zero-Inflated Negative Binomial Regression

Stratify the relations between third places, people seen and well-being

  • Test with significant others (important people, like socializing)?
  • Add information on close/non close relations
  • Different mecanisms by age groups?
  • Specific locations (cultural, park, restaurant)?

Do we keep other gender?

  • 1% of the sample
  • Remove: gain 1 DoF

Do we use age as continuous?

  • Gain 5 DoF
